  <sharedRules>
    <rule id="c531-2ba5-638d-73d5" name="Synapse Creature" hidden="false">
      <description>• Any Tyranid broods with a model within 12&quot; of a Synapse Creature (including the Synapse Creature itself) never fall back and are assumed to automatically pass any Leadership-based test they are  alled upon to make, other than psychic tests and those called upon for target selection. Note that since regrouping only takes place at the start of the turn, a Tyranid unit that falls back can be destroyed by pursuers or by becoming trapped. A Tyranid brood that enters Synapse range may rally regardless of the usual restrictions (enemy models within 6&quot;, etc).

• Tyranids within Synapse range as described above (including the Synapse Creature itself) are immune to the effects of Instant Death caused by weapons with a Strength double the creature&apos;s Toughness. Note that this does not apply to Ripper swarms.

• A creature with the Synapse power is able to cause all Spore Mines within 24&quot; to detonate in the Shooting phase (choose one mine in the cluster as the initial detonation point). Note that this counts as a shooting attack, so it may not shoot or use other psychic powers in the Shooting phase. Other creatures from the same brood may still fire at a different target if desired.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="dea2-e710-8473-b3ed" name="Instinctive Behavior" hidden="false">
      <description>If all models in a Tyranid brood begin their movement phase more than 12&quot; away from a Synapse Creature, and that unit is not falling back or already in combat, it will revert to Instinctive Behaviour.  Choose each brood in this situation in turn, and apply the following rules:
• If you want to move that brood that turn for any reason, it must take a Leadership test at the start of its Movement phase. If this is failed, the brood will fall back as it had failed a Morale test. If it is passed, the brood may act as normal.
• Alternatively the brood may Lurk. This means it will remain stationary that turn but may fire its weapons as normal. Lurking units that are not Monstrous Creatures add +1 to any cover save they may benefit from. Lurking Tyranids may not claim objectives or hold table quarters.
• Tyranids always fall back towards the nearest Synapse Creature if possible if there are no Synapse Creatures on the board they will fall back towards the nearest Tyranid table edge.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="e5fa-b52a-258b-5e3d" name="Shoot the Big Ones!" hidden="false">
      <description>The opposing player&apos;s line of fire is only blocked by terrain, vehicles and models in close combat while shooting at Tyranid models.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="2bcd-07b5-747a-af83" name="Spore Mines" hidden="false">
      <description>Spore Mines drift D6&quot; in a random direction in each Tyranid Movement phase. On a Hit symbol on the scatter dice the Tyranid player may choose the direction of movement. Unlike other models the spore can move within 1&quot; of enemy models, and if they make contact with an enemy model it detonates.
If a Spore Mine makes contact with an enemy, or an enemy unit or vehicle shoots while within 2&quot; of it the mine explodes at the end of the phase. If the mine is reduced to 0 wounds or otherwise killed it will also explode.
Whenever a spore mine explodes it triggers the detonation of all of the other mines in its cluster, regardless of location.
Place a Blast Marker centered over the mine in base contact (do not scatter this marker) and resolve it as a normal barrage with the number of templates equal to the number of mines in that cluster. Then remove the detonated mine(s) from the table.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="959a-831b-05aa-b8cf" name="Scything Talons" hidden="false">
      <description>Tyranid creatures with scything talons count as having two close combat weapons and so gain +1 Attack. Creatures with two sets of scything talons gain +2 Attacks in close combat instead of +1. No more than +2 Attacks can be gained in this way and the number of attacks from ranged weapon-symbiotes is not increased. Note that this is the only way that Tyranids gain extra attacks in close combat for multiple weapons.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="8560-537e-b897-32f0" name="Rending Claws" hidden="false">
      <description>Tyranids with rending claws inflict a wound automatically and ignore armour saves on to-hit rolls of 6. Other successful hits must roll ot wound as normal. If the creature rolls a 6 for Armour Penetration they then can roll an additional dice to determine the total Armour Penetration value.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="0b27-f22b-fa4a-6d79" name="Lash Whip" hidden="false">
      <description>Models in base contact with a creature equipped with a lash whip lose one attack in each Assault phase (to a minimum of 1).</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="cb0b-d474-35ae-5950" name="Implant Attack" hidden="false">
      <description>A model which fails is saving throw when wounded by a creature with an Implace Attack suffers 2 wounds instead of one. Implant attacks do not affect wounds inflicted by bio-plasma.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="38cf-0395-332e-7590" name="Flesh Hooks" hidden="false">
      <description>Creates with flesh hooks count as being equipped with frag grenades. In addition, creatures with flesh hooks count &quot;vertically impassable&quot; pieces like high walls or cliffs as difficult terrain instead.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="5611-7e2e-662f-0506" name="Bio-plasma" hidden="false">
      <description>Creatures with bio-plasma may make a single extra close combat attack, worked out at double the models Initiative. The bio plasma hits on a roll of 4+ regardless of the target type or WS. It inflicts a single hit with a Strength equal to the creature +1 (to a maximum of S10) - this hit is unaffected by the benefits of the monstrous creature special rule</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="48ef-8ce6-3e12-9b20" name="Brood Telepathy" hidden="false">
      <description>Creatures with brood telepathy outside the range of Synapse creatures do not use the instinctive behavior rules, but instead must take Morale and Pinning tests like ordinary troops.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="e0d3-28a5-37fb-1bb4" name="Fleet of Claw" hidden="false">
      <description>Instead of shooting the model can move another D6&quot; in the shooting phase, ignoring penalties for difficult terrain.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="f26e-8b6e-546a-c021" name="Living Artillery" hidden="false">
      <description>For the purposes of mission objectives, the model cannot capture table quarters, hold objectives or count as scoring units.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="3b12-1c99-e197-8b80" name="Catalyst" hidden="false">
      <description>This power may be used once per turn at the beginning of the Tyranid player&apos;s Assault phase and requires a Psychic test to use. If the test is successful, the Tyranid player can nominate a single Tyranid unit that is within 24&quot; of the creature using the power. Models in the affected unit will strike back in close combat even if killed before their turn to attack in Initiative order. The dead models are removed once they have made their attacks.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="db25-94d0-1029-694e" name="Psychic Scream" hidden="false">
      <description>Any enemy units with models within 18&quot; of a creature with this power suffer a -1 to all Leadership tests. If several creatures with the Psychic Scream power are within range of the unit, the modifiers are cumulative.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="1145-b9af-3e5e-f939" name="The Horror" hidden="false">
      <description>Any enemy unit that wishes to assault a creature with this power must take a Morale test. If the test is failed, the unit quails before the horrifying psychic presence of the Tyranid Hive Mind and may not make an assault that turn.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="f50d-26b1-c947-b50d" name="Warp Field" hidden="false">
      <description>Defensive psychic barriers give the create a 2+ Armour Save and a 6+ invulnerable save.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="c933-82a4-d069-b937" name="Without Number!" hidden="false">
      <description>Any brood with Wihtout Number that is removed from play may be brought back into play at the beginning of the next Tyranid turn. It moves onto the board from the Tyranid player&apos;s board edge and has exactly the same profile and armaments as its predecessor. Victory Points are socred as usual for the brood and its replacements as if they were entirely seperate broods.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="d739-cb18-68a3-a035" name="Living Ammunition" hidden="false">
      <description>Any failed roll To Wound made by a weapon with living ammunition may be re-rolled.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="8cd2-040d-f978-68f2" name="Crushing Claws" hidden="false">
      <description>A model with crushing claws substitutes a D6 for its normal number of attacks. Any bonus attacks, for example for charging, scything talons etc are added to the D6 roll. For determining the number of ranged bio-weapon shots the creature has, use its basic number of attacks.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="f58b-cc65-48a2-1f53" name="Bonesword" hidden="false">
      <description>A Hive Tyrant with a Bonesword is permanently under the effects of the Catalyst power. With a successful psychic test taken at the beginning of the Tyranid Assault phase, the Hive Tyrant may use the Bonesword to extend the effects of Catalyst to all broods with a model within 6&quot;.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="371b-43ce-a615-e2c6" name="The Shadow in the Warp" hidden="false">
      <description>All Psychic tests made by the enemy during the game are made on 3D6, discounting the lowest roll. Any Perils of the Warp results are nullified, and the power will pass or fail as normal.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="259c-bdaf-d608-bdfd" name="Acid Maw" hidden="false">
      <description>A creature with an acid maw may re-roll unsuccessful rolls to wound in the first round of close combat.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="eeb5-03a9-e850-3e01" name="Feeder Tendrils" hidden="false">
      <description>A creature with feeder tendrils always count as having the Preferred Enemy special rule. Any Tyranid brood with a model within 2&quot; of the creature also benefit from the same rule.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="08c1-712f-eea3-6e1c" name="Leaping" hidden="false">
      <description>Leaping creatures gain a 12&quot; charge distance and may use their full attacks even if not in base contact with an enemy model.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="16cd-192e-bb9b-2311" name="Mace Tail" hidden="false">
      <description>A creature with a mace tail may make a special close combat attack each turn if more than four enemy models are in base contact with it at the beginning of that Assault phase. This is conducted at Initiative 1 and is 1 attack at creature&apos;s full Strength.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="7938-f768-2241-140b" name="Scythe Tail" hidden="false">
      <description>A creature with a scythe tail may make a special close combat attack each turn if more than four enemy models are in base contact with it at the beginning of that Assault phase. This is conducted at Initiative 1 and is D3 attacks at half the creature&apos;s Strength (rounding down).</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="5996-7085-cb5c-6576" name="Regenerate" hidden="false">
      <description>At the start of each Tyranid turn a surviving model with regenerate rolls a dice for each wound it has lost, and for each 6 rolled that creature regains one lost wound, up to its starting total.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="1d89-dfa4-c4e8-ceac" name="Scuttlers" hidden="false">
      <description>Tyranids with the Scuttlers biomorph benefit from the Scout universal special rule.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="9b21-3bb3-9eaa-4a60" name="Spine Banks" hidden="false">
      <description>A model with spine banks counts as being equipped with frag grenades and a spinefist that may be fired in addition to any other shooting.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="9a76-9f3f-3f0c-64bf" name="Spore Cysts" hidden="false">
      <description>A creature with spore cysts that is not in base contact with the enemy may produce a toxin Spore Mine in the Shooting phase in addition to any other shooting.Roll a dice, on the roll of a 1 the creature takes one wound with no saves allowed. Then place the Spore Mine in base contact with the creature, the Spore Mine counts as its own unit.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="073a-236b-7e9a-31a6" name="Symbiote Rippers" hidden="false">
      <description>Each creature with symbiote rippers increases the number of models it counts as for the purposes of outnumbering if its on the winning side in a close combat by 1.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="050e-9186-5cc6-355a" name="Thornback" hidden="false">
      <description>A thornbacked creature doubles the number of models it counts as for the purposes of outnumbering if its on the winning side in a close combat.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="01fd-1831-7eac-09f0" name="Toxic Miasma" hidden="false">
      <description>Any creature being attacked by, or directing its attacks towards, a Tyranid with toxic miasma reduces its WS by 1.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="39b5-0190-b0e0-b675" name="Tusked" hidden="false">
      <description>Tusked Tyranids gain +2 Attacks when charging instead of +1.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="81e4-7c3c-f92b-3299" name="Shieldwall" hidden="false">
      <description>A Hive Tyrant with a Tyrant Guard may not be picked out as a sperate target from its unit despite the fact it is a Monstrous Creature.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="7163-934b-46dc-56a4" name="Gargantuan Creature" hidden="false">
      <description>A gargantuan creature never has to fall back when in combat with a war machine, it can also still be fired upon in the shooting phase when engaged in an assault with a non gargantuan creature and it counts as 20 models for the purposes of calculating enemy morale after an assault.</description>
    </rule>
    <rule id="664d-4cc1-47f7-6e47" name="Brood Nest" hidden="false">
      <description>If a Brood takes a Brood Nest, then they automatically being the game in reserve. When the Brood arrive from reserve they will deploy within 6&quot; of the nest. They may fire weapons in the turn they arrive, but may not assault.
The Brood nest may be set up anywhere on the table that is more than 18&quot; from an enemy unit, or 12&quot; if no enemy unit can draw line of sight to it. A Brood Nest can always infiltrate regardless of the scenario special rules being used.
If a Brood Nest is destroyed, the Brood cannot use it as an entry point and must enter from their own board edge instead.</description>
    </rule>
  </sharedRules>
  <sharedProfiles>
    <profile id="d401-6ac9-4d50-48f8" name="Warp Blast (Default)" hidden="false" typeId="b399-8a1b-bf0b-c5b7" typeName="Weapon">
